Spring Framework 4.3 (@GetMapping, @Post.evidence:
The `@GetMapping` and `@PostMapping` annotations were introduced in Spring Framework 4.3, released in June 2016. These annotations serve as shorthand for `@RequestMapping` with specific HTTP methods, enhancing code readability and expressiveness. ([docs.spring.io](https://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/4.3.16.RELEASE/spring-framework-reference/pdf/spring-framework-reference.pdf?utm_source=openai))

Prior to this, developers used `@RequestMapping` with the `method` attribute to specify HTTP methods:

```java
@RequestMapping(value = "/example", method = RequestMethod.GET)
public String handleGetRequest() {
    // Handle GET request
}
```

With the introduction of `@GetMapping` and `@PostMapping`, the code becomes more concise and intuitive:

```java
@GetMapping("/example")
public String handleGetRequest() {
    // Handle GET request
}
```

These annotations are part of a set of method-specific annotations introduced in Spring 4.3, including:

- `@PutMapping`
- `@DeleteMapping`
- `@PatchMapping`

These additions aim to simplify the mapping of HTTP requests to handler methods, making the codebase cleaner and more maintainable. ([docs.spring.io](https://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/4.3.16.RELEASE/spring-framework-reference/pdf/spring-framework-reference.pdf?utm_source=openai))
